To subtract 5 from \(\frac{7m+3}{m+2}\), write 5 as a fraction with denominator \(m+2\):

\[
5 = \frac{5(m+2)}{m+2} = \frac{5m + 10}{m+2}.
\]

Now combine over the common denominator \(m+2\):

\[
\frac{7m + 3}{m+2} \;-\; 5
\;=\;
\frac{7m + 3}{m+2} \;-\; \frac{5m + 10}{m+2}
\;=\;
\frac{(7m + 3) - (5m + 10)}{m+2}
\;=\;
\frac{7m + 3 - 5m - 10}{m+2}
\;=\;
\frac{2m - 7}{m+2}.
\]

So the result is

\[
\boxed{\frac{2m - 7}{m+2}, \quad m \neq -2.}
\]

First factor \(z^2-49=(z-7)(z+7)\).  Then

Numerator
= \(\displaystyle \frac{2}{(z-7)(z+7)}+\frac1{z+7}
=\frac{2+(z-7)}{(z-7)(z+7)}
=\frac{z-5}{(z-7)(z+7)}.\)

Denominator
= \(\displaystyle \frac9{z+7}+\frac{12}{z-7}
=\frac{9(z-7)+12(z+7)}{(z-7)(z+7)}
=\frac{21(z+1)}{(z-7)(z+7)}.\)

Hence the whole expression is
\[
\frac{\frac{z-5}{(z-7)(z+7)}}{\frac{21(z+1)}{(z-7)(z+7)}}
=\frac{z-5}{21\,(z+1)},
\]
with \(z\neq7,\,-7,\,-1\).
